<p>To make use of Intel's <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://01.org/linux-thermal-daemon">Linux thermal daemon</a> you first need to emerge <span style="white-space: nowrap;" class="plainlinks" title="External link to https&#58;//packages.gentoo.org for the sys-power/thermald package."><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://packages.gentoo.org/packages/sys-power/thermald"><span style="font-family: monospace; font-size: 95%; color: MidnightBlue;">sys-power/thermald</span></a><span style="color: grey; margin-left: 0.1em; font-size: 70% !important;" class="fa fa-hdd-o fa-fw"></span></span> and enable it via:
</p>
<div class="cmd-box"><div><code style="color: #ef2929; font-weight: bold;">root <span style="color:royalblue;">#</span></code><span class="tripleclick-separator"></span><code>rc-config add thermald</code></div></div>
<p>or
</p>
<div class="cmd-box"><div><code style="color: #ef2929; font-weight: bold;">root <span style="color:royalblue;">#</span></code><span class="tripleclick-separator"></span><code>systemctl enable thermald</code></div></div>
<div class="alert alert-info gw-box" style="padding-top: 8px; padding-bottom: 8px;"><strong><i class="fa fa-sticky-note-o fa-rotate-180"></i> Note</strong><br />With <span style="white-space: nowrap;" class="plainlinks" title="External link to https&#58;//packages.gentoo.org for the sys-power/thermald package."><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://packages.gentoo.org/packages/sys-power/thermald"><span style="font-family: monospace; font-size: 95%; color: MidnightBlue;">sys-power/thermald</span></a><span style="color: grey; margin-left: 0.1em; font-size: 70% !important;" class="fa fa-hdd-o fa-fw"></span></span> 2.0 and above, if the daemon is started with the "--adaptive" option, then it is not necessary to create a thermald.conf.xml file.</div>
